{
  "What are the four main tissue types in the human body?": "",
  "Epithelial, connective, muscle, and nervous": "",
  "Cardiac, smooth, skeletal, and elastic": "",
  "Skin, bone, blood, and fat": "",
  "Organ, organ system, organism, and population": "",
  "The four main tissue types are epithelial (covers surfaces/lines cavities), connective (supports and binds — includes bone, blood, cartilage), muscle (contracts for movement — skeletal, cardiac, smooth), and nervous (transmits electrical signals). Every organ contains combinations of these four tissue types working together.": "",
  "What is homeostasis?": "",
  "The breakdown of food into absorbable nutrients": "",
  "The process of cells dividing to form new tissues": "",
  "The movement of blood through the circulatory system": "",
  "The maintenance of a stable internal environment despite external changes": "",
  "Homeostasis is the body's ability to maintain stable internal conditions (temperature, pH, blood glucose, water balance) even when the external environment changes. It relies on feedback loops — primarily negative feedback — involving sensors, a control center, and effectors. Disruption of homeostasis leads to disease.": "",
  "What is the correct order of biological organization from simplest to most complex?": "",
  "Cell → tissue → organ → organ system → organism": "",
  "Organ → tissue → cell → organ system → organism": "",
  "Cell → organ → tissue → organism → organ system": "",
  "Tissue → cell → organ → organism → organ system": "",
  "The hierarchy of structural organization: cells (basic unit of life) → tissues (groups of similar cells) → organs (two or more tissue types) → organ systems (groups of organs working together) → organism (complete living being). Each level has emergent properties not present at simpler levels.": "",
  "What type of feedback mechanism reverses a change to restore the body to its set point?": "",
  "Neutral feedback": "",
  "Open-loop feedback": "",
  "Positive feedback": "",
  "Negative feedback": "",
  "Negative feedback reverses a change to bring the body back toward its set point — it is the most common feedback mechanism in the body. For example, when blood glucose rises, insulin is released to lower it; when body temperature rises, sweating and vasodilation cool you down. The response opposes the initial change, maintaining stability.": "",
  "Which tissue type lines body surfaces, cavities, and forms glands?": "",
  "Connective tissue": "",
  "Epithelial tissue": "",
  "Muscle tissue": "",
  "Nervous tissue": "",
  "Epithelial tissue covers all body surfaces (skin), lines internal cavities (digestive tract, blood vessels, airways), and forms glands (sweat, salivary, endocrine). It is avascular (no blood vessels — nutrients diffuse from connective tissue below) and sits on a basement membrane. It specializes in protection, absorption, secretion, and filtration.": "",
  "Which tissue type is characterized by abundant extracellular matrix with relatively few cells?": "",
  "Connective tissue is defined by its cells being separated by large amounts of extracellular matrix (ECM). The matrix can be liquid (plasma in blood), gel-like (cartilage), or solid (mineralized bone). This is the opposite of epithelial tissue, where cells are tightly packed with minimal matrix. Connective tissue types include bone, cartilage, blood, fat, tendons, and ligaments.": "",
  "What are the three types of muscle tissue?": "",
  "Epithelial, connective, and nervous": "",
  "Voluntary, involuntary, and automatic": "",
  "Dense, loose, and elastic": "",
  "Skeletal, cardiac, and smooth": "",
  "The three muscle tissue types are skeletal (attached to bones, striated, voluntary), cardiac (heart only, striated, involuntary), and smooth (walls of hollow organs, non-striated, involuntary). Each has distinct structure and function, but all share the ability to contract and generate force.": "",
  "Which muscle type is both striated (has visible banding) AND under voluntary control?": "",
  "Smooth muscle": "",
  "All three muscle types are voluntary": "",
  "Cardiac muscle": "",
  "Skeletal muscle": "",
  "Skeletal muscle is the only muscle type that is both striated and voluntary. Cardiac muscle is striated but involuntary. Smooth muscle is non-striated and involuntary. The striations come from the organized arrangement of actin and myosin filaments into sarcomeres — visible as light and dark bands under a microscope.": "",
  "Which organ system includes the skin, hair, and nails?": "",
  "Muscular system": "",
  "Skeletal system": "",
  "Lymphatic system": "",
  "Integumentary system": "",
  "The integumentary system includes the skin (largest organ), hair, nails, and associated glands (sweat, sebaceous). Its functions include physical protection, temperature regulation, vitamin D synthesis, sensation, and immune defense. The skin alone accounts for about 16% of total body weight.": "",
  "What defines an organ?": "",
  "Any structure visible without a microscope": "",
  "A group of organs working together": "",
  "A structure composed of two or more tissue types that work together to perform a specific function": "",
  "A single type of cell performing one function": "",
  "An organ is a structure made of multiple tissue types that cooperate to perform specific functions. For example, the stomach contains epithelial tissue (lining), smooth muscle (churning), connective tissue (support), and nervous tissue (regulation). A group of organs working together is an organ system, and a single cell type performing one function describes a tissue.": "",
  "What does the term 'avascular' mean when describing epithelial tissue?": "",
  "It has an extensive blood supply throughout": "",
  "It lacks its own blood vessels — nutrients must diffuse from underlying connective tissue": "",
  "It is found only in blood vessels": "",
  "It cannot regenerate after injury": "",
  "Avascular literally means 'without blood vessels.' Epithelial tissue has no blood vessels of its own; instead, oxygen and nutrients diffuse from capillaries in the underlying connective tissue through the basement membrane. Despite being avascular, epithelial tissue regenerates rapidly (skin and intestinal lining replace themselves every few days) because stem cells at the base of the epithelium divide frequently.": "",
  "What is the extracellular matrix (ECM)?": "",
  "The membrane surrounding each individual cell": "",
  "The non-cellular material secreted by cells that provides structural and biochemical support to surrounding cells": "",
  "The nucleus of a cell where DNA is stored": "",
  "The fluid inside the cell cytoplasm": "",
  "The extracellular matrix (ECM) is material found outside cells that provides structural support, anchors cells, and regulates cell communication. Its composition varies by tissue: in bone, the ECM contains calcium phosphate minerals (hard); in cartilage, it contains collagen and proteoglycans (flexible); in blood, the ECM is plasma (liquid). Connective tissue has the most abundant ECM of all tissue types.": "",
  "What is a negative feedback loop?": "",
  "A mechanism that amplifies a response until an external event stops it": "",
  "A regulatory mechanism where the body's response reverses a detected change, bringing conditions back toward a set point": "",
  "A one-time response that cannot repeat": "",
  "A harmful response that causes disease": "",
  "Negative feedback is the body's primary homeostatic mechanism. It has three components: a sensor (detects change), a control center (processes information and determines response), and an effector (carries out the response). The response opposes the initial stimulus — for example, rising blood glucose triggers insulin release, which lowers glucose back to normal. The word 'negative' refers to the reversal of the change, not to something bad.": "",
  "What is a positive feedback loop?": "",
  "The default regulatory mechanism for most body processes": "",
  "A response that restores homeostasis to a stable set point": "",
  "A beneficial response as opposed to a negative (harmful) one": "",
  "A mechanism where the body's response amplifies the initial change, pushing the system further from its starting point until an endpoint is reached": "",
  "In positive feedback, the response enhances and accelerates the original stimulus rather than reversing it. This creates an escalating cycle that only stops when an external event (endpoint) interrupts it. Examples: childbirth (oxytocin → stronger contractions → more oxytocin, until delivery), blood clotting (platelets activate more platelets, until wound is sealed), and action potential propagation. Positive feedback is rare in the body because it disrupts rather than maintains homeostasis.": "",
  "What are intercalated discs?": "",
  "Layers of connective tissue that wrap around muscle fibers": "",
  "Discs of cartilage found between vertebrae in the spine": "",
  "The bands of light and dark seen in skeletal muscle striations": "",
  "Specialized cell junctions found only in cardiac muscle that allow rapid electrical signal transmission between heart cells": "",
  "Intercalated discs are unique to cardiac muscle. They contain gap junctions (allow ions to flow between cells for rapid electrical conduction) and desmosomes (provide strong mechanical connections so cells don't pull apart during contraction). Together, these allow the heart to contract as a synchronized unit — the signal from the SA node spreads rapidly through all cardiac cells via intercalated discs. No other muscle type has this feature.": "",
  "What is an organ system?": "",
  "A single organ performing multiple tasks": "",
  "Any body part that contains muscle": "",
  "A group of organs that work together to perform a set of related functions": "",
  "A group of cells forming a tissue": "",
  "An organ system is a collection of organs that cooperate to perform major body functions. For example, the digestive system includes the mouth, esophagus, stomach, small intestine, large intestine, liver, and pancreas — all working together to break down food, absorb nutrients, and eliminate waste. The human body has 11 major organ systems, each dependent on the others for the organism to survive.": "",
  "What is a basement membrane?": "",
  "A thin extracellular layer that anchors epithelial tissue to underlying connective tissue": "",
  "A layer of smooth muscle beneath the skin": "",
  "The cell membrane of cells located at the bottom of an organ": "",
  "The innermost membrane surrounding the brain": "",
  "The basement membrane is a thin, non-cellular layer composed of proteins (laminin, collagen IV, proteoglycans) that lies between epithelial cells and the connective tissue beneath them. It acts as a structural anchor, a selective filter for molecules diffusing from blood vessels, and a guide for cell migration during wound healing. In cancer, invasion through the basement membrane is a key step in metastasis — it marks the transition from carcinoma in situ to invasive carcinoma.": "",
  "What does 'stratified' mean when describing epithelial tissue?": "",
  "The epithelium is only one cell layer thick": "",
  "The tissue contains both epithelial and connective cells": "",
  "The cells are arranged in a branching pattern": "",
  "The epithelium has multiple layers of cells stacked on top of each other": "",
  "Stratified epithelium has multiple cell layers, providing extra protection in areas of high friction or abrasion. Stratified squamous epithelium lines the skin, mouth, esophagus, and vagina. In contrast, 'simple' epithelium is only one cell thick and is found where rapid diffusion or absorption occurs (lungs, intestinal lining, kidney tubules). The trade-off: stratified = better protection but slower diffusion; simple = faster diffusion but less mechanical resistance.": "",
  "What are vital signs?": "",
  "Genetic markers that determine disease risk": "",
  "Blood test results showing hormone levels": "",
  "Signs that a patient is conscious and alert": "",
  "Measurable indicators of basic body function including body temperature, heart rate, respiratory rate, and blood pressure": "",
  "Vital signs are the four standard measurements of basic physiological function: body temperature (~37°C/98.6°F), heart rate (~60-100 bpm), respiratory rate (~12-20 breaths/min), and blood pressure (~120/80 mmHg). Each reflects the status of multiple organ systems and homeostatic mechanisms. Abnormal vital signs signal homeostatic disruption — a fever indicates immune activation, tachycardia suggests cardiovascular stress, and hypotension may indicate shock.": "",
  "What is smooth muscle?": "",
  "Involuntary, non-striated muscle found in the walls of hollow organs like blood vessels, the intestine, and the bladder": "",
  "The muscle type found only in the heart": "",
  "Voluntary muscle attached to bones for movement": "",
  "A type of connective tissue that stretches easily": "",
  "Smooth muscle is involuntary (not under conscious control), non-striated (lacks visible banding — hence 'smooth'), and has spindle-shaped cells with a single central nucleus. It lines hollow organs: blood vessels (controls blood pressure via vasoconstriction/dilation), intestines (peristalsis for digestion), airways (bronchoconstriction/dilation), bladder (controls urination), and uterus (labor contractions). It is regulated by the autonomic nervous system, hormones, and local chemical signals.": "",
  "A pathologist examines a tissue sample under a microscope and sees tightly packed cells with no blood vessels, sitting on a thin basement membrane. The tissue lines the patient's small intestine. Which tissue type is this, and why is it suited for this location?": "",
  "Nervous tissue — it detects nutrients in the intestinal lumen": "",
  "Smooth muscle — it contracts for peristalsis": "",
  "Dense connective tissue — the collagen fibers protect against mechanical stress": "",
  "Simple columnar epithelial tissue — one cell layer allows efficient nutrient absorption while the tight packing provides a selective barrier": "",
  "Epithelial tissue is identified by tightly packed cells, no blood vessels (avascular), and a basement membrane. The small intestine has simple columnar epithelium — 'simple' (one cell layer) allows nutrients to cross quickly into the blood, while 'columnar' (tall) cells have microvilli that increase surface area for absorption. Deeper layers of the intestinal wall contain smooth muscle (for peristalsis), connective tissue (blood supply and support), and nervous tissue (enteric nervous system), but the surface lining is epithelial.": "",
  "A biology student places these structures in order from simplest to most complex: organelle, cell, tissue, molecule, organ system, organ, organism, atom. Which sequence is CORRECT, and what makes each level different from the one below it?": "",
  "Atom → cell → molecule → organelle → tissue → organ → organ system → organism": "",
  "Molecule → atom → cell → organelle → tissue → organ system → organ → organism": "",
  "Cell → atom → molecule → tissue → organ → system → organism → organelle": "",
  "Atom → molecule → organelle → cell → tissue → organ → organ system → organism — each level has emergent properties not found at simpler levels": "",
  "The hierarchy: atoms (carbon, hydrogen, oxygen) combine into molecules (proteins, DNA), which form organelles (mitochondria, ribosomes), which are components of cells (basic unit of life). Similar cells form tissues (muscle tissue), tissues combine into organs (heart), organs cooperate as organ systems (cardiovascular system), and all systems together form an organism. Emergent properties arise at each level — for example, a single neuron cannot think, but billions organized into brain tissue can produce consciousness.": "",
  "During exercise, your body temperature rises to 39°C. The hypothalamus detects this change and triggers sweating and vasodilation in the skin, which cool you back toward 37°C. A student asks: 'Once the temperature drops back to 37°C, why does the sweating stop?' The answer is:": "",
  "The sweat glands run out of water": "",
  "It is positive feedback that naturally exhausts itself": "",
  "The hypothalamus stops functioning after prolonged activity": "",
  "This is negative feedback — once the sensor detects the set point has been restored, the effector response is shut off": "",
  "Thermoregulation is a classic negative feedback loop with three components: (1) the sensor/control center (hypothalamus) detects a deviation from the set point (37°C); (2) effectors (sweat glands and blood vessels) are activated to reverse the change; (3) once the set point is restored, the sensor detects this and turns off the effectors. The response is self-limiting because it eliminates its own trigger. This is the defining feature of negative feedback — the output feeds back to reduce the input signal.": "",
  "A surgeon notes that the tissue in a patient's Achilles tendon is tough, fibrous, and has very few cells embedded in dense, parallel collagen fibers. A medical student incorrectly identifies it as skeletal muscle. What tissue is it actually, and what feature distinguishes the two?": "",
  "Nervous tissue — tendons transmit stretch signals": "",
  "Epithelial tissue — it lines the surface of the tendon": "",
  "Dense regular connective tissue — identified by abundant collagen matrix with few cells, unlike muscle which has many contractile cells": "",
  "Cardiac muscle — it contracts involuntarily": "",
  "Tendons are dense regular connective tissue — 'dense' because of tightly packed collagen fibers and 'regular' because fibers run in parallel (providing great tensile strength in one direction). The key difference from muscle: connective tissue has few cells in abundant extracellular matrix (collagen), while muscle tissue has many cells (muscle fibers) packed tightly with contractile proteins. Tendons connect muscle to bone and transmit force but do not contract themselves.": "",
  "During childbirth, the baby's head pushes against the cervix, triggering oxytocin release. Oxytocin causes stronger contractions, pushing the head harder against the cervix, releasing more oxytocin. This escalates until delivery. A student confuses this with negative feedback. What makes this POSITIVE feedback?": "",
  "It reverses the initial change to restore homeostasis": "",
  "It self-limits once the set point is reached": "",
  "The response amplifies the original stimulus rather than reversing it — each cycle makes contractions stronger, not weaker": "",
  "It is called 'positive' because it has a beneficial outcome": "",
  "Positive feedback amplifies the stimulus: pressure → oxytocin → stronger contractions → more pressure → more oxytocin. Unlike negative feedback (which reverses a change), positive feedback pushes the system FURTHER from its starting state. It only stops when an external endpoint occurs (the baby is delivered, removing pressure on the cervix). 'Positive' and 'negative' refer to the direction of the response relative to the stimulus, not whether the outcome is good or bad.": "",
  "A histology slide shows tissue with long, multinucleated, striated fibers. The label says it's voluntary. Another slide shows branched, striated cells connected by intercalated discs that beat without conscious control. Which muscle types are on the two slides?": "",
  "Slide 1: skeletal muscle (striated + voluntary + multinucleated); Slide 2: cardiac muscle (striated + involuntary + intercalated discs)": "",
  "Slide 1: cardiac muscle (striated and involuntary, with intercalated discs between cells)": "",
  "Slide 1: smooth muscle (non-striated and involuntary, found in walls of hollow organs)": "",
  "Both slides show the same muscle type at different magnification levels under the microscope": "",
  "Skeletal muscle: striated (sarcomere banding), voluntary, long cylindrical multinucleated fibers (from fused myoblasts during development). Found attached to bones. Cardiac muscle: striated (also has sarcomeres), involuntary, branched cells with single nuclei connected by intercalated discs (gap junctions + desmosomes for synchronized contraction). Found only in the heart. The third type — smooth muscle — is non-striated, involuntary, spindle-shaped with single nuclei, found in hollow organ walls.": "",
  "Blood is classified as a connective tissue, which surprises many students because it is liquid. A student argues it should be its own tissue type. Which structural feature proves blood IS connective tissue?": "",
  "Blood contracts to push itself through vessels, making it muscle": "",
  "Blood transmits electrical signals, making it nervous tissue": "",
  "Like all connective tissues, blood has cells (RBCs, WBCs, platelets) suspended in an abundant extracellular matrix (plasma)": "",
  "Blood lines the inner surface of blood vessels, making it epithelial": "",
  "The defining characteristic of connective tissue is cells embedded in an abundant extracellular matrix. In blood, the ECM is plasma (a liquid ~ 55% of blood volume). The cells include RBCs (oxygen transport), WBCs (immune defense), and platelets (clotting). The same logic applies to other connective tissues: bone cells sit in calcified matrix, cartilage cells in rubbery matrix, fat cells in lipid-rich matrix. It's the endothelium (epithelial tissue) that lines blood vessels, not blood itself.": "",
  "A diabetic patient's blood glucose rises to 250 mg/dL after a meal but fails to come back down. Normally, the pancreas would release insulin to lower glucose back to ~100 mg/dL. A doctor explains that this homeostatic mechanism has failed. Which specific component of the feedback loop is malfunctioning in Type 2 diabetes?": "",
  "The set point has been permanently reset to 250 mg/dL": "",
  "The effector response — target cells are resistant to insulin, so they cannot take up glucose despite the hormone signal": "",
  "The positive feedback loop has become too strong": "",
  "The sensor — the pancreas cannot detect blood glucose levels": "",
  "In Type 2 diabetes, the negative feedback loop for blood glucose fails at the effector level: the pancreas still detects high glucose (sensor works) and still releases insulin (control center works), but target cells (muscle, fat, liver) are insulin-resistant — they don't respond properly to the signal, so glucose stays elevated. In Type 1 diabetes, the failure is different: autoimmune destruction of beta cells means the pancreas cannot produce insulin (control center failure). Both result in chronic hyperglycemia, but the point of failure differs.": "",
  "A patient with severe burns over 40% of their body rapidly loses water through the damaged areas and develops life-threatening bacterial infections within days. An intern asks why losing skin is so dangerous. Which TWO critical functions of the integumentary system explain these specific complications?": "",
  "Temperature regulation and vitamin D synthesis, which are secondary metabolic functions of the skin": "",
  "Hormone secretion and blood cell production, which are endocrine functions carried out by the dermis": "",
  "Waterproof barrier (keratin layer prevents evaporative water loss) and first-line immune defense (physical barrier blocks pathogen entry)": "",
  "Nerve sensation and sweat production, which are primarily controlled by the sympathetic nervous system": "",
  "The integumentary system's waterproof keratin layer prevents evaporative water loss — when destroyed by burns, patients lose massive amounts of water and electrolytes, causing dehydration and shock. Simultaneously, the skin's physical barrier against microorganisms is gone, allowing bacteria direct access to underlying tissues. Infection is the leading cause of death in severe burn patients. While the skin also regulates temperature and synthesizes vitamin D, the question specifically asks about water loss and infection — those map to the barrier and immune defense functions.": "",
  "The small intestine absorbs glucose, which enters capillaries in the intestinal villi and is transported via the blood to liver cells and then to body cells throughout the organism. A student asks why the digestive system 'needs' the circulatory system. Which explanation BEST captures organ system interdependence?": "",
  "Without the circulatory system, absorbed nutrients would remain trapped in the intestinal wall and never reach distant cells that need them": "",
  "The circulatory system digests food before the digestive system absorbs it": "",
  "The nervous system replaces the circulatory system for nutrient transport": "",
  "Each organ system works completely independently — they do not interact": "",
  "This illustrates a core principle: no organ system works in isolation. The digestive system breaks food into absorbable molecules (glucose, amino acids, fatty acids) and absorbs them into the blood. The circulatory system then transports those nutrients to every cell in the body — muscle cells for energy, brain cells for function, growing cells for building materials. Without digestion, there are no nutrients to transport; without circulation, nutrients can't reach distant cells. This interdependence extends to all 11 organ systems.": ""
}